WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.639
Hey there, welcome to the Posit Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:22.000
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.240
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.360
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:43.639
Can't wait to see you there. I am so excited to introduce our featured leader today, Cara

00:00:43.639 --> 00:00:49.240
Thompson, Data Visualization Consultant at Building Stories with Data. Cara, welcome.

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:56.520
How are you doing? Thank you so much. Thank you so much for having me. I would love you

00:00:56.520 --> 00:01:01.000
to introduce yourself, tell us who you are, what you do, and something that you do for

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.639
fun. Okay, so I am Cara Thompson. I live in Edinburgh in Scotland, and I am a Data Visualization

00:01:11.639 --> 00:01:20.680
Consultant. So it's my joy in life to help data teams make the most of Data Viz to communicate

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:26.239
the outcomes of their research really effectively. And I think I found over the years that my

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:33.680
niche has seemed to define itself as helping teams of specialists communicate with a non-specialist

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:39.760
audience. And it's just, yeah, it's great. I enjoy doing that a lot. You can probably guess

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:45.279
some of the things that I do for fun from the stuff that's behind me. I'm a musician. Mike and

00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:54.480
I have talked about this a few times, and I'm convinced that my musical education plays a

00:01:54.480 --> 00:02:02.000
strong part in how I approach data visualization. Is that, would you say your main for fun activity

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.959
is music, or is there anything else that you really like to do outside of data stuff?

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:16.080
I run as well. I enjoy running. I find it's a great, yeah, it's a good headspace generator.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:21.839
I'm a mum of two young girls, and so having, you know, half an hour to an hour where nobody

00:02:21.839 --> 00:02:29.600
is asking me for anything is really wonderful. That's awesome. Well, we at The Hangout here,

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:35.839
Rachel just ran the Boston Marathon. I would just like to put that out there, but that's amazing.

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:41.039
I'm incredibly impressed. I saw a picture of her at mile 25, which is almost the end of marathons,

00:02:41.039 --> 00:02:47.919
like 26.2 miles, right? And she was still smiling. I would have been deflated and a puddle on the

00:02:47.919 --> 00:02:56.320
floor. So you're not alone. The DSH Run Club is definitely a thing. I would love to put forth a

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:02.639
few topics for everybody that I think would be amazing to talk with Cara about. So I will ask

00:03:02.639 --> 00:03:07.520
for a couple of these, but I really encourage everyone to think along these lines. So things

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:14.399
that Cara brings to mind for me, striking out on your own and being a small business owner.

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:19.839
That is a really hard topic. When is it time to do that? How do you know you want to do that?

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:27.759
How hard is it? What does that entail? Also working out loud. Cara is amazing at working out loud,

00:03:27.759 --> 00:03:32.720
and it's something that I feel really passionately about, and I've talked with her about it. I know

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:39.600
that she has amazing things to say about it, but also being interdisciplinary. And this is

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:44.399
where I would like to start with you, Cara. I remember asking you, do you have any sort of

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:52.160
data viz books to recommend? And you said, no, I don't. I don't worry about data viz specific

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:57.199
stuff. I don't worry about data viz specific books or data viz specific conferences because

00:03:57.199 --> 00:04:01.919
I am interdisciplinary and that's what makes me special. So can you talk a little bit more about

00:04:01.919 --> 00:04:08.960
that? Yeah, sure. I mean, I have to say I do have a lot of respect for people who write data viz

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:15.759
books, and I think there is a lot to be learned from them. But I think a huge part of what

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:22.000
makes me approach data viz the way I do is the background that I have. So I grew up in a family

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.040
where we were speaking two languages. So I speak French and English. I speak French with my

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:33.600
daughters. And so there's an element of learning that people process the world in slightly different

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:40.160
ways through different languages, which I think has been useful to me. I enjoy playing music. I

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:46.239
enjoy writing music. If anyone in my group of friends is getting married or having a big party

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:49.760
and they've got some musical friends, I'll try and write parts for everyone so that it all works

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:58.399
well together. And so that is part of it. Mum is a brilliant artist. She paints. And so she used

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:03.440
to take us around art galleries growing up. And there's a lot to be said for just being curious

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:10.799
about how other people use shapes, colour, movement, and how across all these things we

00:05:10.799 --> 00:05:16.720
encode information, whether it's language, music, visual arts. We're all encoding it and then

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:22.559
decoding it. And it's just something that I have always found fascinating. And so I took the

00:05:22.559 --> 00:05:27.760
multidisciplinary thing through to my degree. I did a degree which was a joint degree in music and

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:32.799
psychology, which I really enjoyed because when I got bored of writing my psychology essays, I would

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:36.239
write a piece of music and then I would get stuck on that and I would go back to writing the

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:43.200
essay and back and forth, which was great. It also taught me a lot about managing multiple deadlines,

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:49.279
which I didn't always succeed at doing as a student. But it was fun. And so I think I did

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:56.399
that as an undergrad. Then I did psycholinguistics for my masters and then in the PhD revisited how

00:05:56.399 --> 00:06:02.160
the brain reacts to strange things in music and language, how we process patterns, what we can

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:09.760
learn from that as to how we're wired to be excited by new stuff. And yeah, I just love

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:13.200
hanging out with people who are interested in different things to me because I think we've

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:21.119
always got a lot to learn from each other. That's wonderful. I think that you dropped a few fun

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:26.079
facts on us and I will drop a fun fact. I see them in the chat, too. I love everybody's fun

00:06:26.079 --> 00:06:30.880
facts. I'm reading them. My fun fact is probably that I am an anthropology

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:38.160
nerd and an archaeology nerd. I am obsessed with it. If you find me outside of work times,

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:43.119
I'm probably reading or watching something historical, especially like historical sewing

00:06:43.119 --> 00:06:50.320
is very, very exciting to me. And I wanted to sort of stay on this topic a little bit because

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:56.000
you mentioned to me museum displays that you really like the way that you see things done.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:01.359
And you also said, like, how do comic books do this? How do we present things visually?

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:04.799
Can you talk a little bit about some of your favorite inspirations that are comic books?

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:12.000
Yeah, of course. I mean, so comic books are a really big thing in France and, you know,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.559
they are throughout the world, but French kids will tend to grow up reading Asterix at some point

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:21.119
and Tintin. You know, there's a lot to be learned from Tintin. It's actually historically

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:25.679
quite useful. There's some stuff that you have to, you know, reimagine a little bit nowadays. But

00:07:26.239 --> 00:07:32.480
I think, you know, growing up with that notion of telling stories through pictures has been quite

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:36.880
fun. So how do you know, you know, if there's a speech bubble on its own in a little box,

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:40.799
how do you know who that belongs to? How do you infer what has happened between image one and

00:07:40.799 --> 00:07:46.079
image two? How is movement communicated? How do you see the different angles that people are

00:07:46.079 --> 00:07:52.799
looking at? And then it's really fun seeing different cultures. So like Japanese comics would

00:07:52.799 --> 00:07:56.959
be quite different from European comics in terms of how shapes and movements and stuff are

00:07:56.959 --> 00:08:03.040
translated. And there's quite a lot of similarity between the two, but also really interesting

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:09.440
differences to look at. And then you've got the thing about, you know, the more specific a

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:13.279
person's face is, the less likely you are to identify with them. So if you make a more generic

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:17.920
face, people are more likely to identify with the character. And if you think about, you know, the

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:26.559
IKEA flat pack furniture instructions, very generic people that are drawn in there. And I guess

00:08:26.559 --> 00:08:29.839
that's another interdisciplinary thing, you know, growing up building flat pack furniture. That was

00:08:29.839 --> 00:08:35.760
me and dad. That's what we did together. Dad's the musician in the family. But, you know, growing up

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:41.119
with him, both of us used to like, really like that problem solving. Like we had, where did this

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:45.599
piece go? How did they, why did they draw it this way around? And I think for a while as a kid, I

00:08:45.599 --> 00:08:51.119
thought maybe, you know, drawing IKEA instructions books could be, you know, one of my future jobs.

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:55.039
It's just been really interesting thinking about that notion of translating something complex into

00:08:55.039 --> 00:09:02.400
something easy has been a thread all the way through. I love that you just said that because

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:08.159
I, no joke, considered at one point in my life, maybe I could be the person who designs LEGO

00:09:08.159 --> 00:09:13.599
instructions because I find fault with them often. I'm like, why did they do it like this?

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:17.200
It should be positioned a different direction. It should be this way. And they should make that a

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:22.000
different color. And my eyes can't tell the difference between those, which I would love to

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:27.440
meet somebody who does that one day or someone who designs museum displays. Well, I'd love to ask you

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:33.520
a little bit about your background because you mentioned your master's and your PhD, love that

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:40.799
that was super interdisciplinary. What did you do after the PhD that got you to where you are right now?

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:47.760
Yeah, so after the PhD, so my PhD was in how the brain reacts to weird things in music and language.

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:53.840
There wasn't a huge amount of funding for pursuing that at postdoc level and then going into academia,

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:58.960
although that had been my intention. So I applied for a bunch of postdocs and didn't

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:04.640
really get anywhere with that. But where I did end up was teaching research methods to

00:10:05.599 --> 00:10:09.520
students who were enrolled on a psychology module within a music department.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:14.559
And so that was really fun because these were people who hadn't come from a research background

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:20.400
at all, but they were doing music psychology stuff. If you think about music therapy or the

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:26.799
potential community involvements in music programs, they wanted to do some research that could

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:31.679
help to emphasize the impact of what they were doing. And so my task was to give them what they

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:37.280
needed to do that, to do it well, to write it up. And that was really fun. So I did that for

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:44.320
for an academic year. And during that time, a job came up at the Royal College of Surgeons in

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:49.840
Edinburgh. So in order to be a surgeon in the UK, you have to pass one of the Royal College of

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:56.559
Surgeons exams in order to become a consultant. And so these exams are really, really important.

00:10:56.559 --> 00:11:02.239
They're career defining for people. If you can't get through that way, there are

00:11:02.239 --> 00:11:06.880
alternative routes, but they're less straightforward. And so the exams are really

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:11.440
important. They're really high stakes. And it's really important to get it right. And an exam,

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:18.159
like a research design study, is a measurement tool. So the task was figure out how precise

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:24.080
the measurement tool is, figure out how we could make it more precise, help the surgeons understand

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:30.960
the imprecision, the implications of that. And what do we do with candidates who achieve exactly

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:35.760
the pass mark? Are they having a good day and actually they're not really safe to be let loose

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:41.520
on people? Or are they really competent and they're having a bad day? And these were all

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:47.359
things that required the surgeons to grasp statistical concepts in terms of the relationship

00:11:47.359 --> 00:11:53.599
between the items in the exam, probabilities, false positives, all this kind of stuff.

00:11:54.159 --> 00:12:00.559
And surgeons are not used to not understanding stuff because they've always been top of the

00:12:00.559 --> 00:12:05.599
class. It's something that they found quite disconcerting. And so I think what I really

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:12.239
enjoyed with them was meeting them with explanations that they could really grasp

00:12:12.239 --> 00:12:18.479
really well enough to make informed decisions. And data visualization became a key component of that.

00:12:18.479 --> 00:12:23.200
So rather than bamboozling them with statistical concepts, I would show them the data and we could

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:28.000
see, right, here's the pattern. This is what it looks like. These are the implications. What do we

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:35.359
want to do about it? And so it was just really, really interesting to be in that world of,

00:12:35.359 --> 00:12:40.320
you know, communicating education data to specialists in a completely different field

00:12:41.119 --> 00:12:46.559
and helping them feel confident that they were making sensible decisions for the exam.

00:12:46.559 --> 00:12:52.479
So I did that for about a decade and during that time got more and more excited about data

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:59.200
visualization. And then I went on maternity leave with my first daughter and discovered the tidy

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:05.919
Tuesday challenge. It was COVID. I needed something to keep my brain going with the

00:13:05.919 --> 00:13:11.359
coding side of things. And my maternity leave got extended because of the lockdowns. So I thought,

00:13:11.359 --> 00:13:17.440
right, I'll get involved in this. This looks like fun. And it was great. And it really, you know,

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:22.000
it really transformed things for me. And that's where the learning out loud in R came from,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:27.200
although I think I've always been keen on learning out loud. But doing it in the R community,

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:32.559
people were so welcoming. It was a real confidence boost at a time when I desperately needed it.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.960
And so I'm just so grateful that that challenge was there at a time when I needed it. And I'm

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:44.479
grateful that it's still there, that it continues. And it's a source of inspiration for so many.

00:13:45.119 --> 00:13:48.799
So yeah, seeing what other people were doing, like, how nice did they do that? And then you

00:13:48.799 --> 00:13:53.039
find the code, you're like, okay, okay, that makes sense. I can, I can, I can do something.

00:13:53.039 --> 00:13:57.679
And so then you build on it and figure out how it works and build your own stuff that people go,

00:13:57.679 --> 00:14:01.679
how did she do that? And then you go, well, here you go. Here's the code. And seeing other people

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:08.080
building on the stuff that I've done is just really, really rewarding. It's a magical feeling.

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:13.599
I want to shout out tidy Tuesday. If you don't know what tidy Tuesday is, there are no rules

00:14:13.599 --> 00:14:17.760
around tidy Tuesday. This isn't something where it's like, you need to know how to participate.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:24.239
Tidy Tuesday is a repository that contains hundreds of data sets that are real world.

00:14:24.239 --> 00:14:31.440
They're interesting. They are topical. And they are just CSV files. You don't have to access them

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:38.000
in any specific way. You can just access them as a CSV file, save them, call them, reading them in

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:43.679
in whatever language you like. And we all get together each week with this new data set that

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:50.080
the data science learning community curates. And we work on it out loud, right? Like whatever that

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:54.640
means to you, share it on social media, maybe share a screenshot of what you're doing. If it's

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:59.359
data viz, that's an easy thing to share. But I really recommend that whatever language you use,

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:05.039
Python, R, Julia, Excel, do whatever you can get involved in the community and share.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:14.239
All righty. I would love to hop to Slido and get some questions going. Mike, you asked a question

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:18.479
that everybody likes. You got lots of upvotes, and I like it too. Would you like to ask that?

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:26.880
Sure. So the question goes something like, can you talk a little bit about the differences between

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:32.640
the kind of infographics that you might see in the media, like BBC website or Financial Pounds,

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:39.280
and the kind of what I'm calling death by data viz that we get in pharma industry or for

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:49.599
publications or for the kind of regulated industries? Because it seems that there's very

00:15:49.599 --> 00:15:56.960
little in common. I mean, I would love for some of those publication visualizations to be closer to

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:02.960
your best practices and those kinds of more easy to read, easy to understand concepts.

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:09.039
But can you just kind of, why would people do those kind of really nasty data visualizations?

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:18.080
And what can we stop doing? Yeah. I think there's an element of you do what you know,

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:25.359
right? So if your field has always produced this specific type of visualization using this tool

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:35.840
that everybody uses, then you just go with it. If the aim is to communicate just within your field,

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:40.320
then that's going to be the path of least resistance, A, in terms of time investment,

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:46.719
B, in terms of getting other people who are familiar with that to understand it. But I think

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:53.039
there is a real case to be made that people, I think probably since the pandemic and more data

00:16:53.039 --> 00:16:57.359
was being shared during that time publicly, people have got more used to seeing visualizations,

00:16:57.359 --> 00:17:03.760
people are more willing to engage with them outside of the specialist fields. And so if we

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:09.599
want that to be done well, then we maybe do need to start engaging a little bit more with formats

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:18.880
that have been more successful in more mainstream media. I think there's, yeah, it's probably a

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:25.599
question of priorities as well. You know, I feel I had to fight quite hard against imposter syndrome

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:29.280
when I would go to conferences and see all these people doing really cool stuff with the data,

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:33.839
and I was like, I just make it look pretty. But actually making it look pretty, it's not just

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:37.680
about making it pretty, is it? It's about making it more functional, making it more accessible,

00:17:39.439 --> 00:17:46.479
making it easy for people to understand. So yeah, I think it's probably priorities, it's time,

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:51.040
and it's that people see it and think, oh gosh, I don't have the skill to do that, whereas in actual

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:58.959
fact, you know, people can build up the skills to do these kind of things. So yeah, I'm with you,

00:17:58.959 --> 00:18:06.880
Mike, in terms of wanting to make academic publications have higher quality visual. Well,

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:11.280
I'm not even going to say high quality, actually, because I think people do put a huge amount of

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:16.400
effort into the visualizations that go into academic publications, and it's more, you know,

00:18:16.959 --> 00:18:22.000
trying to encourage people to think about the impact of how they style things on the audience's

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:26.560
reception of the message. Does that answer your question?

00:18:28.719 --> 00:18:32.880
He might not be able to unmute, but I'm going to say yes, thank you.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.199
Okay, I'll take that, that's good.

00:18:35.199 --> 00:18:39.920
I might not be able to, like, quick draw on you, Mike. Thank you, Mike, for that.

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:48.560
Sorry, I think that is right. There's an element of I don't have time, but then other people may

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:52.719
not. You're essentially wasting other people's time if you're obfuscating what's in your plot.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:19:00.880
Also, like, good and effective is so subjective, and all of our eyes work differently, and all of

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:04.800
our brains work differently, and I think that's a really interesting challenge to navigate.

00:19:05.599 --> 00:19:13.439
Alrighty, I would love to have Inga ask their question. I will highlight it here.

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:18.079
Let me see if I can find you to unmute you.

00:19:18.079 --> 00:19:18.640
I just did.

00:19:19.359 --> 00:19:20.319
Yay, awesome.

00:19:21.199 --> 00:19:28.719
Hi, everyone. Thank you, Kara, for being here. My question is kind of coming from a place where I

00:19:28.719 --> 00:19:33.599
feel overwhelmed often by sort of the number of data tools and packages available for any

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:38.079
given task or project, so I'm wondering if you have thoughts on, like, how do you decide what to

00:19:38.079 --> 00:19:43.920
use and for what purpose, and then how do you balance between sort of deepening a focused

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:49.839
skill set versus expanding your toolkit by learning new things, new packages and tools?

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:58.239
Yeah, that's a great question. The overwhelm is real, I think, for everyone, so don't feel bad

00:19:58.239 --> 00:20:04.800
about that. That's probably a good thing, you know, to realize in a sense how small we are in

00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:12.800
a huge field. You know, it's good. It keeps us wanting to learn. I would say the thing that I

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:19.199
encourage people to do when I'm giving data viz workshops is start from where you are, so

00:20:19.199 --> 00:20:23.599
think about the types of data that you are currently interacting with, and think about the

00:20:23.599 --> 00:20:27.920
