but also for remembering the people behind the data, and also remembering the, you know,

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:41.439
the ecological impact of all the queries that are running, which is not not negligible as well.

00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:50.959
Awesome, thank you. Thanks Joey for the question. Alrighty, I have an anonymous question here, which

00:39:51.439 --> 00:39:58.479
goes all the way back to the beginning, to ask about why the data science transition. And I want

00:39:58.479 --> 00:40:04.239
to say that we've covered this anonymous question asker. I just want to make sure, like that you

00:40:04.239 --> 00:40:09.600
said that you don't have a lot of like straight data science in your background, which there hasn't

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:16.159
been straight data science as far as a discipline for a really long time. But when you were

00:40:16.159 --> 00:40:21.280
actually doing the transition, my question is, were you even thinking about it as data science?

00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:28.080
Or was this just Kara following her heart and doing visualization, because that's what she

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:33.600
found interesting? Yeah, no, I wasn't thinking about it as data science. So my background's

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:41.840
in psychology. I grew up on SPSS in psychology, if people can remember that. I'm 41, and so at

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:45.919
the time when I was studying, data science wasn't really a thing, or it was a very new thing,

00:40:45.919 --> 00:40:52.000
or it was a very niche thing. And data visualization as a field wasn't really a thing either.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:55.280
And it's been interesting seeing a few other people similar age to me, similar specialism to

00:40:55.280 --> 00:41:00.239
me, talking about this, and about how the different things that are in their backgrounds led

00:41:00.239 --> 00:41:07.840
them to where they are now. I got into coding because I was interested in seeing how

00:41:07.840 --> 00:41:12.639
much we could automate all the pointing and clicking that we were doing in SPSS. So I joined

00:41:12.639 --> 00:41:17.840
the Royal College of Surgeons. The task was to analyze exams. And if you're doing all that

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:22.639
in SPSS, you're doing the same thing time and time again. You can write SPSS syntax, if anyone's given

00:41:22.639 --> 00:41:29.280
that a go, welcome to the club. But in terms of producing reports, producing really

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:34.159
good visualizations, being flexible when a new question came in, that was a lot more difficult

00:41:34.159 --> 00:41:38.800
to do. So I thought, oh, there's this thing called R, I should give that a go. So I taught myself R

00:41:38.800 --> 00:41:43.280
to try and automate the reports, ended up doing that quite well, which meant that we

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:49.760
could then process a lot more exams than we had done previously. And then, you know,

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:54.959
caught the bug. I was like, oh, what else can we get it to do? But it was very much thinking of it as a tool

00:41:54.959 --> 00:42:01.280
to do the job of helping people understand the statistics, rather than thinking about it as,

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:06.080
you know, exploring the tool for the sake of the tool itself. And I think that's probably

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:12.959
where I am in terms of my understanding of what I do. I wrestled with what I should call

00:42:12.959 --> 00:42:16.560
myself for a long time. You know, when you fill in these official forms and they're like, well, you

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:20.719
know, what is your job title? Like, data viz consultant doesn't fit anywhere. So am I a data

00:42:20.719 --> 00:42:27.360
scientist? Well, maybe, but, you know, only tangentially. So yeah, I think the transition

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:34.560
from academia into data science was more of following a topic that I was interested in,

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:40.159
following a task that I was interested in, and then finding the tools that happened to be data

00:42:40.159 --> 00:42:47.760
science tools to continue to do that well. Awesome. Thank you. I love the SPSS conversation

00:42:47.760 --> 00:42:53.040
that's going on in the chat right now. A bunch of us going, yep, SPSS is actually still alive and

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:59.840
well. I learned that a lot of my professors were educational psychology professors. And so that's

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:04.639
what they taught in their applied statistics courses. I actually really kind of miss SPSS

00:43:04.639 --> 00:43:09.679
sometimes. It's just the point and click that I don't love. You're right. Doing things over and

00:43:09.679 --> 00:43:14.000
over again, you're like, this could be easier. And especially when you get to the end of something in

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:19.040
SPSS and you realize you have to go back and do it differently. You're like, oh no, I have to go

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:23.439
back to the start of the yellow brick road. And I have to re-click all of those things in the same

00:43:23.439 --> 00:43:30.959
order, but with one step slightly different. That is the magic of parameterized and coding and

00:43:30.959 --> 00:43:38.479
scripting. So thank you so much for that question. And I will mark that one as answered. Sonya has

00:43:38.479 --> 00:43:47.360
a question here. Sonya, are you available to unmute and ask? I am. With AI just becoming

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:56.719
such a big topic these days, I want to know what parts of your job you see being automated by AI?

00:43:58.719 --> 00:44:03.280
And if AI has right now or even if you see it in the future impacting your business,

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:12.959
and if so, in what ways? Yeah, good question. And the honest answer is I haven't actually

00:44:12.959 --> 00:44:19.679
explored AI all that much. And so I've used it for write me a step-by-step instruction for how

00:44:19.679 --> 00:44:27.040
to do this thing on this device that I don't know. I've used it for get me the right regex string

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:31.199
that I need. Although there is something so satisfying about getting that right yourself

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:37.760
from the get-go. It's one of those, oh, did I do it? Yes, it worked. So I haven't really,

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:43.040
I don't really use it at all regularly. Just every now and then for troubleshooting,

00:44:43.040 --> 00:44:48.399
but then it doesn't always get to the right answer anyway. I think sometimes there is a

00:44:48.399 --> 00:44:52.560
tendency to think that AI can do everybody else's job, but not your own. So I've seen a lot of

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:57.600
people talking about how it can be useful for cleaning up data. I've worked with Crystal. I've

00:44:57.600 --> 00:45:03.360
loved working with Crystal. And I know that I would trust Crystal way more than I would trust

00:45:03.360 --> 00:45:09.360
an algorithm to do that kind of stuff right. So I think there are specialisms that we don't

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:15.760
always appreciate in other people's work that we think can be delegated, which I think is a bit of

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:24.800
a dangerous way to be thinking. To me, there's stuff about checking the accessibility of color

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:29.120
palettes, for example. There are a few AI tools that are coming up in that field that are really

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:34.159
quite exciting, or you can say tweak this and bring this in, and that's good. But then you still

00:45:34.159 --> 00:45:36.800
have to test it. You still have to check that it's doing the right thing. You have to check that it's

00:45:36.800 --> 00:45:44.719
not compromised on the creative vision that the client had. So I think using it for get me from

00:45:44.719 --> 00:45:50.399
this place to the next step is something that I can see it doing really well. I think there are

00:45:50.399 --> 00:45:53.360
people who are throwing all sorts of stuff at it and coming up with all sorts of stuff at the other

00:45:53.439 --> 00:46:02.479
end, which there's room for it to grow. It's still fairly new in terms of its impact. I think

00:46:02.479 --> 00:46:07.360
maybe in terms of business day-to-day running, there's maybe a little bit more

00:46:08.879 --> 00:46:13.040
where it could be useful than necessarily in the super specialized skills.

00:46:14.560 --> 00:46:21.439
Where I really do not like it being used is people who use it to churn out a whole bunch of content

00:46:21.439 --> 00:46:27.840
online and just, oh, do we need that? Does the world need that? Does the planet need us to use

00:46:27.840 --> 00:46:34.560
its resources in that way? I'm not convinced. Does it add anything? I don't know. But, yeah,

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:41.520
I think using it wisely, no problem at all, but being aware of the need for specialists

00:46:41.520 --> 00:46:47.520
still would, I think, keep us on the right track. Absolutely. And I think that this

00:46:47.679 --> 00:46:53.520
leads us right into our next question, which is an anonymous one on Slido.

00:46:55.520 --> 00:46:59.840
What are some common pitfalls in DataVis and how can you avoid them?

00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:07.040
Yeah, I mean, there are pitfalls. There are so many of them. One of the pitfalls is to just do

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:12.000
what you've always done and stay comfortable within that. I think that comes back to Mike's

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:18.719
question earlier. Sometimes it's best to ask for forgiveness than ask for permission when it comes

00:47:18.719 --> 00:47:25.280
to trying out new ideas in DataVis. I think a common one is to just throw too much information

00:47:25.280 --> 00:47:32.159
at people and to have it all be at the same kind of level of perceived hierarchy. So if you're

00:47:32.159 --> 00:47:36.800
putting a lot of text into a visualization, people are going to spend a lot of time reading that.

00:47:37.600 --> 00:47:43.679
If you pare it back a little bit, that's helpful. If you organize it visually, so you add some text

00:47:43.679 --> 00:47:49.280
hierarchy into it, making sure that people process it in an order that's logical, then that will help

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:56.080
as well. Often as data people, we come at things with like, oh, look at all this data, look at all

00:47:56.080 --> 00:48:02.080
these patterns, how can I show them all? When in actual fact, the question is, what do my users need?

00:48:02.879 --> 00:48:07.919
What is the first thing that should stand out from the visualization and what could I put

00:48:07.919 --> 00:48:13.919
behind the curtain, either with some interactivity or with extra graphs in it? I think that to me

00:48:13.919 --> 00:48:20.159
is a big pitfall that I see a lot. It's that desire to show everything that you've done

00:48:20.879 --> 00:48:26.879
in a graph, which isn't super helpful for the people. Yes, I love that answer so much because

00:48:26.879 --> 00:48:32.159
it sort of feels like giving a presentation where you're like, I want them to see how much work I

00:48:32.159 --> 00:48:40.000
did. So I am going to put in all of this stuff, right? And in reality, you did your job and what

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:44.399
they need to know is just like one-tenth of what you want to throw at them. I will also say,

00:48:47.120 --> 00:48:54.959
this is a pitfall of giving a workshop. I have attended, I'm going to say, over 50 data workshops

00:48:54.959 --> 00:49:02.239
in the past, I don't know, four years. And the best workshops are ones where they're led by

00:49:02.239 --> 00:49:07.679
someone like Nicola Reni, who will stick to one thing and teach you that one thing.

00:49:08.879 --> 00:49:13.840
And they're not trying to throw a billion different things in there and they're not going, oh, just,

00:49:13.840 --> 00:49:20.719
you know, go complete all of these different empty or half-empty scripts with all of the things that

00:49:20.719 --> 00:49:26.639
you just learned because no one's going to retain 50 concepts in the 10 minutes that you gave them.

00:49:26.639 --> 00:49:32.719
So yes, for sure. I think that there are some amazing questions left in our Slido,

00:49:32.719 --> 00:49:36.239
but we have six minutes left. So let's get one more in here.

00:49:38.479 --> 00:49:43.360
And I really think that this one is really cool, but I wonder if it's too long.

00:49:44.320 --> 00:49:53.760
It was down here from Nessa, and Nessa, I am going to ask it really quickly so that we can

00:49:53.760 --> 00:49:57.840
squeeze it in. It's, have you ever had to convince people to care about data visualization?

00:50:01.679 --> 00:50:09.120
Yes, yes, I think, yes, I do. I tend to speak at conferences which aren't data-vis focused

00:50:09.120 --> 00:50:13.679
because the people who go to the data-vis focused conferences already care about visualization,

00:50:13.679 --> 00:50:18.000
and it's the people who go to the other conferences that sometimes I feel I need to speak to more.

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:24.879
So yes, there is definitely the group of people who say, well, this is just making it pretty.

00:50:24.879 --> 00:50:31.199
I don't need that. Or do we even need it at all? One of the things that I do at the start

00:50:31.199 --> 00:50:38.479
of a workshop that I give regularly is set up this really silly scenario about needing to go

00:50:38.479 --> 00:50:43.760
to the palmer penguins' islands and needing to see two different species of penguins, but I am

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:48.719
terrified of penguins with long beaks. That's the kind of premise of it. Help me plan my trip.

00:50:48.719 --> 00:50:52.800
And then I give them the standard academic write-up of how many penguins are on each island

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:57.040
and what the mean beak length is on each island, all that kind of stuff. And that's not super

00:50:57.040 --> 00:51:00.800
helpful. Then we move to a table, which isn't very helpful. Then we move to a table that's

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:05.760
been stylized, which is a little bit more helpful. Then we move to an ugly graph of all the data,

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:10.320
and then we move to a graph where I've spent some time organizing it visually so that it makes

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:15.280
sense, and suddenly the story stands out. And I think a lot of the time we think it's a lot of

00:51:15.280 --> 00:51:21.520
extra effort for us to do it, but the effort that's reduced from the users is really worth it.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:29.040
So I think sometimes, yeah, if people are looking to argue that DataVis isn't worth the time,

00:51:29.600 --> 00:51:34.399
then spending a little bit of time and then showing them the impact that it can have is a

00:51:34.399 --> 00:51:37.360
better way to do it than just going through conversationally.

00:51:39.199 --> 00:51:43.520
Wonderful. Thank you so much for the amazing question, Nessa. We have just a few minutes

00:51:43.520 --> 00:51:48.800
left and I would love to end with sharing your LinkedIn. I'm going to share that in the chat

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:53.360
right now, and asking you if you have any parting words of career advice for us.

00:51:54.080 --> 00:52:01.919
Good question. I think earn a reputation for being a good person to work with,

00:52:03.919 --> 00:52:10.719
and that is a holistic good. Okay, so you can be super skilled at this thing,

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:17.840
but put people off with your approach, or you can be slightly less skilled and bring people in

00:52:18.239 --> 00:52:24.239
and encourage them and be a good team player. And I know which of those two I would prefer to work

00:52:24.239 --> 00:52:32.320
with. So I think that to me is a big piece of career advice. Get good at your skill,

00:52:32.320 --> 00:52:38.320
focus in on something that you think you could be world-class at, hone that craft, but don't

00:52:38.320 --> 00:52:44.560
neglect relationships, they are so important. Yeah, be a good community member with your skill.

00:52:44.800 --> 00:52:50.639
I love that so much. I will echo all of that. I would also say, like, think about what makes

00:52:50.639 --> 00:52:57.280
somebody great to be around, and ask yourself if you are putting that energy out into the world as

00:52:57.280 --> 00:53:03.600
well. For example, I have a friend named Joanna, who always, when she is presented with a challenge

00:53:03.600 --> 00:53:08.879
to something that she believes or that she just stated, she will go, huh, that's fair. Like,

00:53:08.879 --> 00:53:13.360
she doesn't fight it, she doesn't say, no, I'm right, and you're wrong, and here's why.

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:18.000
She's so receptive to just being like, oh, yeah, I hadn't thought about that. And I realized through

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:23.840
knowing my friend Joanna, that I really, really value that, and that that's so welcoming and

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:29.760
wonderful in other people, in friends, and coworkers, and bosses, and managers, whatever.

00:53:29.760 --> 00:53:34.719
Somebody who is willing to just be like, oh, I was wrong, or, oh, I didn't realize that, or,

00:53:34.879 --> 00:53:39.199
oh, I just learned something new. That's just such an impressive and wonderful quality

00:53:40.080 --> 00:53:43.600
that I admire in everybody. It's why I admire you, Kara, because all of your posts

00:53:44.479 --> 00:53:50.080
exude that energy. All right, everybody, thank you so much, Kara. This was amazing.

00:53:51.679 --> 00:53:53.600
Thanks for having me. It's been really fun.

